anks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Alex  , used only as a feminine name. Its formation has probably been influenced by   Alice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alix Adèle de Thiers-Châlon was born about 1149, in Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France. She had at least 1 daughter with Guy de Bâgé. She died about 1204, in Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Rhône-Alpes, France, at the age of 57."},"et":{"ABT 1149–ABT 1204":"umbes 1149–umbes 1204","1177–1219":"1177–1219","1200–1252":"1200–1252","1149–1204":"1149–1204","1204":"1204","1149":"1149","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1252":"1252","ABT 1149":"umbes 1149","ABT 1204":"umbes 1204","1219":"1219","Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Rhône-Alpes, France":"Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1149–ABT 1204":"noin 1149–noin 1204","1177–1219":"1177–1219","1200–1252":"1200–1252","1149–1204":"1149–1204","1204":"1204","1149":"1149","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1252":"1252","ABT 1149":"noin 1149","ABT 1204":"noin 1204","1219":"1219","Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Ranska","Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Ranska","Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Rhône-Alpes, France":"Bâgé-le-Châtel, Ain, Rhône-Alpes, Ranska"},"fr":{"ABT 1149–ABT 1204":"environ 1149–environ 1204","1177–1219":"1177–1219","1200–1252":"1200–1252","1149–1204":"1149–1204","1204":"1204","1149"